<div class="page-h1">Martin Luther King, Jr.</div>
<p class="timeline-intro">An American pastor, activist, humanitarian, and leader in the African-American Civil Rights Movement.</p>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-long"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-vertical"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-short"></div>
<div class="timeline-date"><span class="month">January</span> 15, 1929</div>
<h2>Birth.</h2>
<p>Michael King—later known as Martin Luther King, Jr.—is born to the Reverend Martin Luther King, Sr. and Alberta Williams King in Atlanta, Georgia.</p>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-long"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-vertical"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-short"></div>
<div class="timeline-date">1944</div>
<h2>Morehouse College.</h2>
<p>He graduates high school at the age of 15 and enrolls at Morehouse College.</p>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-long"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-vertical"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-short"></div>
<div class="timeline-date">1948</div>
<h2>Crozer Theological Seminary.</h2>
<p>King is awarded a bachelor of arts degree in sociology and enters Crozer Theological Seminary.</p>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-long"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-vertical"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-short"></div>
<div class="timeline-date">1951</div>
<h2>Boston University.</h2>
<p>He graduates from Crozer with a bachelor of divinity degree and begins his graduate studies at Boston University.</p>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-long"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-vertical"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-short"></div>
<div class="timeline-date"><span class="month">June</span> 18, 1953</div>
<h2>Marriage.</h2>
<p>King marries Coretta Scott.</p>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-long"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-vertical"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-short"></div>
<div class="timeline-date"><span class="month">June</span> 5, 1955</div>
<h2>PhD.</h2>
<p>He receives a doctorate in systematic theology from Boston University.</p>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-long"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-vertical"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-short"></div>
<div class="timeline-date"><span class="month">January</span> 30, 1956</div>
<h2>Home bombing.</h2>
<p>While he speaks at a mass meeting at First Baptist Church, his home is bombed. His wife and ten-week-old daughter are home but uninjured. King later pleads for a peaceful response from an angry crowd in front of his home.</p>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-long"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-vertical"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-short"></div>
<div class="timeline-date">1957</div>
<h2>National visibility.</h2>
<p>He is named chairman of the Southern Negro Leaders Conference on Transportation and Nonviolent Integration—later known as the Southern Christian Leadership Conference (SCLC)—and appears on the cover of Time Magazine. During the Prayer Pilgrimage for Freedom, he delivers his first public address, &#8220;Give Us The Ballot,&#8221; at the Lincoln Memorial.</p>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-long"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-vertical"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-short" id="jt"></div>
<div class="timeline-date"><span class="month">September</span> 1958</div>
<h2>Stride Toward Freedom:<br />The Montgomery Story.</h2>
<p>King publishes his first book, &#8220;Stride Toward Freedom: The Montgomery Story,&#8221; his memoir of the Montgomery bus boycott, which he describes as &#8220;the chronicle of 50,000 Negroes who took to heart the principles of nonviolence, who learned to fight for their rights with the weapon of love, and who in the process, acquired a new estimate of their own human worth.&#8221; During a book signing at Blumstein’s Department Store in Harlem, he is stabbed by Izola Ware Curry. A seven-inch letter opener is removed from his chest at a Harlem hospital.</p>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-long"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-vertical"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-short"></div>
<div class="timeline-date">1959</div>
<h2>India.</h2>
<p>On a month-long visit to India, he meets with Prime Minister Jawaharlal Nehru and many of Gandhi’s followers.</p>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-long"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-vertical"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-short"></div>
<div class="timeline-date"><span class="month">October</span> 1960</div>
<h2>Rich&#8217;s sit-in.</h2>
<p>King is arrested at a sit-in demonstration at Rich’s department store in Atlanta. In the same month, he is sentenced to four months hard labor for violating a suspended sentence he received for a traffic violation in 1956.</p>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-long"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-vertical"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-short"></div>
<div class="timeline-date">1962</div>
<h2>Jailed.</h2>
<p>He is arrested at a prayer vigil in Albany, Georgia, and spends two weeks in jail.</p>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-long"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-vertical"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-short"></div>
<div class="timeline-date"><span class="month">April </span>16, 1963</div>
<h2>&#8220;Letter from Birmingham Jail.&#8221;</h2>
<p>With his &#8220;Letter from Birmingham Jail,&#8221; he responds to eight Jewish and Christian clergymen’s advice that African Americans wait patiently for justice.</p>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-long"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-vertical"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-short"></div>
<div class="timeline-date"><span class="month">August</span> 28, 1963</div>
<h2>&#8220;I have a dream.&#8221;</h2>
<p>More than 200,000 demonstrators convene a the Lincoln Memorial for the March on Washington, where King delivers his &#8220;I Have a Dream&#8221; speech before meeting with President John F. Kennedy and Vice President Lyndon B. Johnson in the White House.</p>
<div class="video-embed"><iframe width="100%" height="100%" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/smEqnnklfYs?rel=0&amp;controls=0&amp;showinfo=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-long"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-vertical"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-short"></div>
<div class="timeline-date">1964</div>
<h2>Nobel Peace Prize.</h2>
<p>After being named &#8220;Man of the Year&#8221; by Time Magazine and publishing his book &#8220;Why We Can’t Wait,&#8221; King becomes the youngest person ever to receive the Nobel Peace Prize, declaring that &#8220;every penny&#8221; of the $54,000 award will be used in the ongoing civil rights struggle.</p>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-long"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-vertical"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-short"></div>
<div class="timeline-date"><span class="month">March</span> 1965</div>
<h2>Selma.</h2>
<p>Ten days after &#8220;Bloody Sunday,&#8221; King helps lead civil rights marchers from Selma to Montgomery after a U.S. District judge upholds the right of demonstrators to conduct an orderly march.</p>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-long"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-vertical"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-short"></div>
<div class="timeline-date"><span class="month">June</span> 1966</div>
<h2>&#8220;March Against Fear.&#8221;</h2>
<p>King resumes James Meredith’s &#8220;March Against Fear&#8221; from Memphis to Jackson, Mississippi, after Meredith was shot near Memphis.</p>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-long"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-vertical"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-short" id="jt"></div>
<div class="timeline-date"><span class="month">April</span> 4, 1968</div>
<h2>Assassination.</h2>
<p>The day after delivering his final speech, &#8220;I’ve Been to the Mountaintop,&#8221; at Mason Temple in Memphis, King is fatally shot on the balcony of the Lorraine Motel.</p>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-long"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-vertical"></div>
<div class="timeline-lines-hor-short" id="jt"></div>
<div class="timeline-date"><span class="month">January</span> 20, 1986</div>
<h2>Martin Luther King, Jr. Day.</h2>
<p>On the third Monday in January, Americans observe the first Martin Luther King, Jr. Day three years after President Reagan signs a law declaring the federal holiday.</p>
